erbs, case and, most prominently, spatial prepositions. All ancient language data are fully explained in linguistic word-by-word glosses and are therefore accessible to scholars who are not themselves experts on the respective languages. Taken together, these contributions extend the scope of research on spatial grammar back to the third millennium BCE.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access. Unless otherwise specified individually in the content, the work is licensed under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-NoDerivatives (CC BY-NC-ND) license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/3.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCognitive grammar. 0aLanguage and languagesxGrammarsxHistory. 0aLanguages, ModernxGrammar, Historical. 0aPsycholinguistics. 0aSpace and time in languagexHistory. 0aSpatial behavior. 4aAdpositionen. 4aBewegungsverben. 4aKasus. 4aRaumlinguistik. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh  aLinguistics of space.  aadpositions.  acase.  amotion verbs.1 aBrosch, Cyril, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeorgakopoulos, Thanasis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKutscher, Silvia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKutscher, Silvia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNikitina, Tatiana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpano, Marianna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteinert, Ulrike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStenger, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWerning, Daniel A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato